Nigeria on Wednesday recorded 856 COVID-19 infections. Here are five updates about the pandemic this Thursday. Panama makes COVID vaccination mandatory for public officials Panama has asked all public officials to get vaccinated against COVID-19 or undergo weekly testing. Speaking at a news briefing, Luis Sucre, health minister, said President Laurentino Cortizo has signed a decree mandating public officials to receive three doses of the COVID vaccine or provide proof of a negative test each Monday. Sucre said the directive would take effect from January 28. “If there is something that cannot be stopped, it is the government institutions that have to continue to function,” Sucre said. Thailand raises COVID alert level to curtail spread of Omicron Thailand has raised its COVID-19 alert level as a result of rising infections caused by the Omicron variant.The country change from level three to four which means that measures such as closing high-risk areas and placing restrictions on domestic travel will be activated. “Thailand has entered a new wave of infections, where new cases will be rising fast,” Kiattiphum Wongrajit, permanent secretary of the health ministry, said. “Level four means we may close high-risk places and announce more measures.” Nigeria records 856 infections Nineteen states and the federal capital territory (FCT) recorded 856 COVID-19 cases on Thursday raising the country’s total infections figure to 245,404. A breakdown of the infections is as follow;
Lagos-337
Kaduna-152
FCT-87
Gombe-47
Delta-43
Kano-31
Kwara-27
Enugu-26
